<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-536-483  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 536 483.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Oct 15 1990 n291 p24(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Target: the corporate PBX; toll fraud shifts from telecom carriersto private switchboards. (includes related article on detectingand preventing toll fraud through corporate PBXs)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caldwell, Bruce; Soat, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Criminal computer hackers, known as 'crackers,' and phone phreaks,their telephone counterparts, are shifting their attention fromtheft of long distance services from phone companies to committingtoll fraud through invasion and use of corporate PBXs.andP;  TheCommunications Fraud Control Assn estimates that total losses dueto toll fraud are at least $500 million, or about 1 percent of thetelecommunications industry's gross revenue.andP;  The change intargets is a result of telephone companies more activelyprosecuting toll-call fraud.andP;  This shift has resulted in a 90percent drop in the theft of long-distance services.andP;  The crackersand phone phreaks can still access the long-distance networksthrough far less secure corporate switchboards.andP;  Some companieshave experienced losses of up to several hundred thousand dollars.andO;Methods used to exploit long-distance services through PBXs arediscussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer HackersPBXLong-Distance Telephone ServicesFraudCommunications ManagementMethodsSecurity Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Types of computer crimes. (graph)How to detect PBX fraud. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>